MR. ROOPE. I also believe that letter to be Pillin's writing;
John Pillin
is in the King's Bench - the paper bears a faint resemblance to his writing; I think the name Pillin is written by him - it is in pencil.

WILLIAM BROWN. I am a clerk to Masterman and Co., bankers, Nicholas-lane;
John William Cropper
and Co., have no account at our house, nor have Cropper and Thomas - no such firm is known at our house.

ANDREW HINRICH. I am a solicitor, of No. 9, John-street, Adelphi; my offices are there; my dwelling house is at Brompton - Conway was in my service as clerk for ten or eleven months up to the 25th of April; I usually leave business about six o'clock, sometimes later - (looking at a letter) - I believe this to be Conway's hand-writing; I have often seen him write - I believe the body of it to be his hand-writing -I cannot speak to the name of "Horne;" I believe the name "B. M. Carew," to be his hand-writing, but as to the "Horne," I do not know; I believe the whole to be his hand-wirting, except the name "B. W. Horne," and I believe the direction to be his hand-writing- (looking at the back of the cheque) - here is " J. Wood, Long-acre, 10th April:" I cannot say whose hand-writing it is - it does not appear to me to resemble Conway's writing; I should rather believe it was not - the words"Long-acre" resemble it more than any other; I should say the "Long-acre" resembled it - that is all I can say;
James Wood
is a client of mine, and resides in Longacre; Benjamin Worthy Horne, the coach-proprietor, was a client of mine, and lives at the Golden Cross, Charingcross; I think the signature on this letter resembles Horne's writing; I know Mr. Wood's writing - the writing on the back of the cheque bears no resemblance to Wood's writing; I have raised Conway's salary at times - he applied to me for a loan of money; he wrote me a letter on the subject; I do not think he repeated it personally, and I took no notice of the letter; my client's letters are occasionally about the office; I have not got the letter he sent to me - I do not know what has become of it. I think I destroyed it; I have not a doubt in my own mind that I did do so.
